         <abstract>
            <p>
               On page 1 of his book Algebraic Numbers and Diophantine Approximation, K. B. Stolarsky posed the problem of solving the equation $y^2 + 999 = x^3$ in positive integers. In the present paper we refine some techniques of Ellison and Pethö and show that the complete set of integer solutions of Stolarsky's equation is $$x = 10, y = \pm1, x = 12, y = \pm27, x = 40, y = \pm251, x = 147, y = \pm1782, x = 174, y = \pm2295,$$ and $$x = 22480, y = \pm3370501.$$ 
            </p>
          </abstract>
